{"question_id": "Q004", "question": "Why does TabNet argue that tabular data is difficult for standard deep neural networks?", "ground_truth": "TabNet argues that standard deep networks are often poorly suited to tabular data because they lack the right inductive bias, can be overparameterized for tabular decision boundaries, and are often outperformed by tree-based methods that are efficient, interpretable, and fast.", "category": "definition_explanation", "difficulty": "medium", "policy": "maddpg_ceb", "data_source": "live_llm", "final_status": "accepted", "final_answer": "Tabular data has yet to see success with a canonical architecture, unlike images, text, and audio, which have shown notable success with deep neural networks.", "token_f1": 0.2069, "rouge_l": 0.0909, "correctness": 0.2069, "faithfulness": 1.0, "citation_support": 1.0, "source_precision": 1.0, "source_recall": 1.0, "verification_pass": 1, "unsupported_claims": 0, "latency_seconds": 44.6479, "num_llm_calls": 3, "token_usage": 2488, "num_steps": 4, "trace": [{"step": 1, "agent": "retriever", "action": "hybrid_rerank", "params": {"dense_sparse_weight": 0.35348835587501526, "top_k": 24, "rerank_threshold": 0.5781125500798225, "source_diversity": 0.6832260489463806}, "reward": -0.02, "done": false}, {"step": 2, "agent": "grader", "action": "medium_filter", "params": {"relevance_threshold": 0.6088238209486008, "evidence_keep_ratio": 0.2926447242498398, "strictness_score": 0.6734640747308731}, "reward": -0.07, "done": false}, {"step": 3, "agent": "generator", "action": "generate_answer", "params": {"temperature": 0.49089273251593113, "citation_strictness": 0.2745122164487839, "max_tokens": 806, "answer_detail_level": 0.6784276962280273}, "reward": -0.07, "done": false}, {"step": 4, "agent": "verifier", "action": "verify_answer", "params": {"support_threshold": 0.4054485186934471, "confidence_threshold": 0.13572588562965393}, "reward": 0.6735, "done": true}]}
{"question_id": "Q005", "question": "How do the encoder and decoder stacks differ in the Transformer architecture?", "ground_truth": "The encoder has repeated layers with self-attention and feed-forward sublayers, while the decoder adds an extra sublayer that attends over the encoder output and also uses masked self-attention so it cannot look ahead to future positions.", "category": "intra_paper_comparison", "difficulty": "medium", "policy": "maddpg_ceb", "data_source": "live_llm", "final_status": "accepted", "final_answer": "The decoder stack differs from the encoder stack by having an additional sub-layer that performs multi-head attention over the output of the encoder stack.", "token_f1": 0.3019, "rouge_l": 0.2154, "correctness": 0.3019, "faithfulness": 1.0, "citation_support": 1.0, "source_precision": 0.3333, "source_recall": 1.0, "verification_pass": 1, "unsupported_claims": 0, "latency_seconds": 42.4399, "num_llm_calls": 3, "token_usage": 2337, "num_steps": 4, "trace": [{"step": 1, "agent": "retriever", "action": "hybrid_rerank", "params": {"dense_sparse_weight": 0.6051717475056648, "top_k": 27, "rerank_threshold": 0.6877609342336655, "source_diversity": 0.6646744906902313}, "reward": -0.02, "done": false}, {"step": 2, "agent": "grader", "action": "medium_filter", "params": {"relevance_threshold": 0.597205713391304, "evidence_keep_ratio": 0.17939329147338867, "strictness_score": 0.698952242732048}, "reward": -0.07, "done": false}, {"step": 3, "agent": "generator", "action": "generate_answer", "params": {"temperature": 0.5842115804553032, "citation_strictness": 0.3384411334991455, "max_tokens": 673, "answer_detail_level": 0.5566527470946312}, "reward": -0.07, "done": false}, {"step": 4, "agent": "verifier", "action": "verify_answer", "params": {"support_threshold": 0.4587462991476059, "confidence_threshold": 0.13650760054588318}, "reward": 0.6279, "done": true}]}
{"question_id": "Q006", "question": "How does BERT's masked language model objective differ from next sentence prediction?", "ground_truth": "Masked language modeling predicts masked tokens from context within the input, while next sentence prediction trains the model to decide whether sentence B truly follows sentence A.", "category": "intra_paper_comparison", "difficulty": "medium", "policy": "maddpg_ceb", "data_source": "live_llm", "final_status": "accepted", "final_answer": "BERT's masked language model objective and next sentence prediction task are two separate pre-training objectives used in BERT. \n\nThe masked language model objective is described in Section 3.1 Pre-training BERT, where it is mentioned that the model randomly masks some of the tokens from the input and the objective is to predict the original vocabulary id of the masked token.\n\nOn the other hand, the next sentence prediction task is described in Section 3.1 Pre-training BERT, where it is mentioned that the model is trained to predict whether two given sentences are adjacent in the original text or not. \n\nThe key difference between the two objectives is that the masked language model objective focuses on predicting the masked tokens in a single sentence, while the next sentence prediction task focuses on understanding the relationship between two sentences.", "token_f1": 0.3256, "rouge_l": 0.1882, "correctness": 0.3256, "faithfulness": 1.0, "citation_support": 1.0, "source_precision": 1.0, "source_recall": 1.0, "verification_pass": 1, "unsupported_claims": 0, "latency_seconds": 186.3216, "num_llm_calls": 6, "token_usage": 10523, "num_steps": 9, "trace": [{"step": 1, "agent": "retriever", "action": "hybrid_rerank", "params": {"dense_sparse_weight": 0.3559148460626602, "top_k": 24, "rerank_threshold": 0.5782694146037102, "source_diversity": 0.6833053827285767}, "reward": -0.02, "done": false}, {"step": 2, "agent": "grader", "action": "medium_filter", "params": {"relevance_threshold": 0.604